### Tested versions

- Reproducible in Godot v4.4.1.stable.official [49a5bc7b6].  I tested on a second machine with the exact same version of Godot and the bug is reproducible there as well.

EDIT: (I'm starting to think that I'm an idiot and it's not a bug, but an intended feature. Because it seems to be reproducible in every version I tested)

- Also reproducible in Godot v4.4.1.stable.official [4c311cbee].

- Also reproducible in Godot v4.5.rc2.official [2dd26a027]

- Also reproducible in Godot 4.3stable.mono.official [77dcf97d8].

Though I had to change the Normal shader so it could run in 4.3. This is the shader: 

```
shader_type spatial;
render_mode unshaded, fog_disabled;

uniform sampler2D depth_texture : hint_depth_texture;

void vertex() {
	POSITION = vec4(VERTEX.xy, 1.0, 1.0);
}

vec3 reconstruct_world_position(vec2 uv, float depth, mat4 inv_proj_matrix, mat4 inv_view_matrix) {
	vec3 ndc = vec3(uv * 2.0 - 1.0, depth); // Use this for forward renderer

	vec4 view = inv_proj_matrix * vec4(ndc, 1.0);
	view.xyz /= view.w;

	vec4 world = inv_view_matrix * view;
	return world.xyz;
}

void fragment() {
	vec2 uv_center = SCREEN_UV;
	vec2 uv_right = SCREEN_UV + vec2(1, 0) / VIEWPORT_SIZE;
	vec2 uv_top = SCREEN_UV + vec2(0, 1) / VIEWPORT_SIZE;

	float depth_center = texture(depth_texture, uv_center).x;
	float depth_right = texture(depth_texture, uv_right).x;
	float depth_top = texture(depth_texture, uv_top).x;

	vec3 center = reconstruct_world_position(uv_center, depth_center, INV_PROJECTION_MATRIX, INV_VIEW_MATRIX);
	vec3 right = reconstruct_world_position(uv_right, depth_right, INV_PROJECTION_MATRIX, INV_VIEW_MATRIX);
	vec3 top = reconstruct_world_position(uv_top, depth_top, INV_PROJECTION_MATRIX, INV_VIEW_MATRIX);

	vec3 world_normal = normalize(cross(top - center, right - center));

	ALBEDO = world_normal;
}
```

EDIT2:
Adding a World3d in the editor to the SubViewport. And doing "SubViewport.own_world_3d = true" in gdscript seems to fix the issue. But then I would have to duplicate all game objects for each SubViewport. Doesn't seem to be a good feature for performance. Is it really an intended feature? What is the correct way of doing this without duplicating all game objects for each viewport?

### System information

Windows 11 - Godot v4.4.1.stable.official - Vulkan (Forward+) - Integrated Intel Arc Graphics
Second machine: Windows 11 - Godot v4.4.1.stable.official - Vulkan (Forward+) - Nvidia RTX 4060. (Also reproducible)

### Issue description

SubViewports seem to act like screens (or windows) and show in the preview viewport and when playing the scene, even if their ViewportTexture is not assigned to anything. If you add a Camera3d and a MeshInstance3d with a QuadMesh as a child of the SubViewport then the QuadMesh is visible even when the ViewportTexture is not attached to anything. And if you add a Normal shader, the shader affects the whole World3d, without attaching the ViewportTexture to any object. The scene renders with the Normal shader.

I will attach the test scene where I reproduced the bug.

The shader I'm using is this one: https://godotshaders.com/shader/world-normals-from-screen-depth/

In the file I also added a Redtest.gdshader, it's a simple shader to add color to the QuadMesh. It's visible with that one, even without assigning the ViewportTexture.

### Steps to reproduce

1. Create Main Scene.
2. Create a second scene with game objects to test the main scene, add a camera here as well.
3. Instance the second scene in Main scene.
4. Add a Subviewport as child of the root node of Main scene.
5. add a Camera3d and a MeshInstance3d as child of the Subviewport. Change Current to off in the SubViewport camera. (To make even more sure that it shouldn't be rendering anything, and still does). Also works if the MeshInstance3d is child of the Camera3d.
6. Change Camera near value to the minimum of 0.001. (This is just so it's easier to see the MeshInstance3d)
7. Add a QuadMesh to the MeshInstance3d.
8. Change QuadMesh size to 2x2.
9. Turn Flip faces On, on the QuadMesh.
10. Move MeshInstance3d to -0.005 in the Z axis. (This is just so the camera can see it).
11. Add the Normal Material to the MeshInstance3d. (I added this one: https://godotshaders.com/shader/world-normals-from-screen-depth/).
12. With the normal material the shader affects the whole world. If you reproduce the Main scene you can now see the shader material. Even without assigning the ViewportTexture to anything.
13. You can also add the RedTest.gdshader material (Or any material that adds color to the ALBEDO) to the MeshInstance3d, to see that it is visible in the preview viewport and when playing the scene, also without attaching the ViewportTexture to anything. (To be able to see the MeshInstance3d with this shader you have to turn Flip faces off.

